<solution><div><h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>We are given a hyperbola with foci <m>F: \hspace{3px} (</m><m>{13}</m><m>,</m> <m>{-3}</m><m>)</m> and <m>F': \hspace{3px} (</m><m>{-11}</m><m>,</m> <m>{-3}</m><m>)</m>, and which contains the point <m>(</m><m>{13}</m><m>,</m> <m>{29}</m><m>)</m>.</p>

<br/>

<p>(a) The <alert>center</alert> of the hyperbola is the midpoint of the two foci. 
<br/>Therefore, this hyperbola has center at <m>(</m> <m>{1}</m> <m>,</m> <m>{-3}</m> <m>)</m></p>

<br/>

<p>(b) The <alert>principal axis</alert> of the hyperbola is the line passing through both of the foci. 
<br/>Therefore, this hyperbola has principal axis <m>{y=-3}</m></p>

<br/>

<p>(c) The <alert>transverse axis</alert> of the hyperbola is the line segment between the two vertices of the hyperbola. We will call the two vertices <m>V</m> and <m>V’</m>, which are the points of the hyperbola which lie on the principal axis.
<br/>Since the hyperbola has rotational symmetry about the center, the distance between the two vertices is twice the distance between the center and one of the vertices.</p>
<p><m>|VV'| = 2|CV|</m></p>

<p>By definition, for any point on the hyperbola, the difference between the distance to each focus is constant. 
<br/>We call this constant <m>2a</m>, and our aim is to write the distance <m>|CV|</m> in terms of this constant.</p>

<br/>

<p>Since the center, vertex and focus are collinear, we have the following relationships,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>|CV| + |VF| = |CF|</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>|VF’| = |CV| + |CF’| = |CV| + |CF|</m></p>
<p>Then, subtracting the first equation from the second,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>|VF’| - |VF| = 2|CV|</m></p>

<p>Since the vertex is a point on the hyperbola, by definition we know that <m>|VF’| - |VF| = 2a</m>.
<br/>Therefore, <m>|CV| = a</m></p>

<br/>

<p>However, <m>a</m> is a constant which we can determine since we know a point on the hyperbola.</p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{False}}</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:30px"><md number="yes">
<mrow>2a \amp = \big| |PF’| - |PF| \big|</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = \big| {\sqrt{{\left(13-13\right)}^2+{\left(29+3\right)}^2}} - {\sqrt{{\left(13+11\right)}^2+{\left(29+3\right)}^2}} \big|</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = | {32} - {40} |</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = {8}</mrow>
<mrow>a \amp = {4}</mrow>
</md></p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{True}}</m></p>

<p>Therefore <m>|CV| = {4}</m>, so the length of the transverse axis is given by,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>|VV’| = |CV| + |CV’| = {8}</m></p>

<br/>

<p>(d) Since <m>|CV| = |CV’| = {4}</m> and <m>V, V’</m> lie on the principal axis <m>{y=-3}</m>, we conclude that,</p> 
<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>V = ({5}, {-3})</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:30px"><m>V’ = ({-3}, {-3})</m></p>

<br/>

<p>(e) For each of the points, we can check whether the difference between the distance to each focus is equal to <m>2a = {8}</m></p>


<br/>
<p style="margin-left:30px">
(i)
Writing <m>Q_{1}: \hspace{3px} (</m><m>{-13}</m><m>,</m> <m>{-29}</m><m>)</m>, we have</p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{False}}</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:60px"><md number="yes">
<mrow>\big| |Q_{1}F’| - |Q_{1}F| \big|
    \amp = \big| \sqrt{{{\left(-13-13\right)}^2+{\left(-29+3\right)}^2}} - \sqrt{{{\left(-13+11\right)}^2+{\left(-29+3\right)}^2}} \big|</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = | {\sqrt{1352}} - {\sqrt{680}} |</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = {13\cdot 2^{\frac{3}{2}}-2\cdot \sqrt{170}}</mrow>
</md></p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{True}}</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">Therefore, <m>Q_{1}</m> <alert>does not</alert> lie on the hyperbola.</p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{True}}</m></p>

<br/>
<p style="margin-left:30px">
(ii)
Writing <m>Q_{2}: \hspace{3px} (</m><m>{-11}</m><m>,</m> <m>{29}</m><m>)</m>, we have</p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{False}}</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:60px"><md number="yes">
<mrow>\big| |Q_{1}F’| - |Q_{1}F| \big|
    \amp = \big| \sqrt{{{\left(-11-13\right)}^2+{\left(29+3\right)}^2}} - \sqrt{{{\left(-11+11\right)}^2+{\left(29+3\right)}^2}} \big|</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = | {\sqrt{1600}} - {\sqrt{1024}} |</mrow>
<mrow>\amp = {8}</mrow>
</md></p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{True}}</m></p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">Therefore, <m>Q_{2}</m> <alert>does </alert> lie on the hyperbola.</p>
<p hidden=""><m>{\mathbf{True}}</m></p>
</div></solution>
